#Text=Egypt protests :
#Text=Army say they will not use force on demonstrators as Mubarak announces cabinet
#Text=Tuesday , February 1 , 2011
#Text=Egyptian army soldiers monitor protests over the weekend .
#Text=Image : Ramy Raoof .

#Text=The president of Egypt has suffered a " devastating blow " after the country 's army announced they would not use force against their own people , who continue to protest against the government tonight .
#Text=The news came hours after six journalists who reported on the protests were released from custody .
#Text=Hosni Mubarak yesterday announced a new cabinet , which does not include several figures who protesters largely do not approve of .
#Text=Analysts have , however , suggested little had changed within the government ; many positions , they say , are filled with military figures .
#Text=Army will ' not use force '
#Text=To the great people of Egypt , your armed forces , acknowledging the legitimate rights of the people ... have not and will not use force against the Egyptian people . — Egyptian army statement

#Text=In a statement broadcast on state media in Egypt , the army said : " To the great people of Egypt , your armed forces , acknowledging the legitimate rights of the people ... have not and will not use force against the Egyptian people . "
#Text=A BBC correspondent in Cairo said the announcement meant it " now seems increasingly likely that the 30-year rule of Mr Mubarak is drawing to a close . "
#Text=" The presence of the army in the streets is for your sake and to ensure your safety and wellbeing .

column1: #Text=Journalists released
#Text=Earlier today , six journalists from the independent news network Al-Jazeera were released from custody after being detained by police .
#Text=The U.S. State Department criticized the arrests ; equipment was reportedly confiscated from the journalists .
#Text=HAVE YOUR SAY
#Text=Have you been affected in some way by this unrest ?
#Text=Tell us your thoughts .
#Text=Add or view comments
#Text=Egyptian officials yesterday ordered the satellite channel to stop broadcasting in the country .

#Text=Al-Jazeera said they were " appalled " by the government 's decision to close its Egyptian offices , which they described as the " latest attack by the Egyptian regime to strike at its freedom to report independently on the unprecedented events in Egypt . "
#Text=In a statement , the news agency added : " Al-Jazeera sees this as an act designed to stifle and repress the freedom of reporting by the network and its journalists .

column1: #Text=Protests continue
#Text=Protesters in Tahrir Square on Sunday .
#Text=Image : Mona .

#Text=A reported 50,000 campaigners , who are demanding the long-time leader step down and complaining of poverty , corruption , and oppression , filled Tahrir Square in Cairo today , chanting " We will stay until the coward leaves . "
#Text=It is thought 100 people have so far died in the demonstrations .
#Text=Today there have been protests in Suez , Mansoura , Damanhour , and Alexandria .
#Text=Speaking to news media in the area , many protesters said the new cabinet did little to quell their anger .
#Text=" We want a complete change of government , with a civilian authority , " one said .
#Text=Another added : " This is not a new government .
